@node not48 "WARPUP RELEASE 4 NOW AVAILABLE"

@{B}WARPUP RELEASE 4 @{UB}NOW AVAILABLE
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

The  release  4  of  @{B}WarpUP @{UB} mainly  features  numerous enhancements, which were
desired  by  developers  so  that  they can work on their projects as easily and
efficiently  as  possible. It is to be expected that quite soon software will be
released requiring @{B}WarpUP 4 @{UB}to be installed.

@{B}WarpUP 4 @{UB}also wants to build a bridge across different worlds. With the addition
of  the  @{B}PowerUP @{UB} Emulation  of  @{I}Frank  Wille @{UI}the possibility is provided to run
@{B}PowerUP @{UB} applications  under @{B}WarpOS@{UB}, so that even these applications can benefit
from  the  outstanding multitasking capabilities of @{B}WarpOS@{UB}. The enclosed version
already supports the new features of @{B}WarpUP 4@{UB}.

@{I}Most important news@{UI}

  * The  memory  management  of  @{B}WarpOS @{UB} was completely replaced. The new memory
    management  is  about  factor  4-5 faster than the old one, this means, that
    applications  which  intensively allocate/deallocate memory using the @{B}WarpOS@{UB}
    functions  will  benefit. Thanks a lot to @{I}Frank Wille @{UI}for the implementation
    of the new memory management.

  * Together  with  the  new  memory management a pooled memory API is provided,
    which is identical to the corresponding API of exec.

  * The semaphore features of @{B}WarpOS @{UB}were enhanced much. Now 'shared semaphores'
    and message based semaphore obtaining/releasing are supported.

  * Now  the meaning of the task signals can be changed using 'SetExceptPPC', so
    that  an  exception  handler  is  executed,  if  such a signal is sent. This
    function  corresponds  to  the  appropriate  exec  function  with some minor
    difference (which certainly is documented in the autodocs).

  * Now it is possible to add interrupt handlers to @{B}WarpOS@{UB}, which can be invoked
    both  by  the  @{B}PPC@{UB}-  and  the @{B}68K @{UB}side. With that a new way of communication
    between  @{B}68K @{UB} and  @{B}PPC @{UB} is  provided,  which  will  be  important  for  some
    specialized applications.

  * In  the past it was quite painful to make sure, that new tasks started using
    'CreateTaskPPC'  get the r2 of their mother task (which means, that they can
    access  the  mother task's variables). Now a new flag was added, which makes
    it very easy to achieve the same result.

  * The creation of @{B}PPC @{UB}tasks from the @{B}68K @{UB}side was made easier by providing the
    function  'CreatePPCTask'.  This  function  itself  calls  the  @{B}PPC @{UB}function
    'CreateTaskPPC'.

  * A  new  env  variable  'powerpc/seginfo' enables a new debugging capability.
    Whenever a task crashes, segment information (hunk/offset pairs) are printed
    out  to  sushi  resp. the serial interface. These information can be used to
    identify  the location of the command which caused the crash. If desired the
    whole stackframe is scanned and all locations of higher-level function calls
    are  also printed out. This new feature requires the 'segtracker' tool to be
    installed.

  * The  installer  of  @{B}WarpUP  V4 @{UB} was  revised and made more secure. Now it is
    almost  impossible  to  install  @{B}WarpUP @{UB} the  wrong  way,  because  most env
    variables  can't  be  configured anymore using the installer. These variable
    are set in a way which should care for maximal reliability.

@{I}Most important bugfixes@{UI}

  * A  problem  with  the terminator 2 was fixed, which could lead to @{B}WarpUP @{UB}not
    starting on some @{B}BlizzardPPC @{UB}systems.

  * The  famous  'ramlib'  problem  was again improved. Again it should be noted
    that  these  'ramlib' problems only can appear when @{B}PPC @{UB}shared libraries are
    used  (since there are still people around which see this issue as advantage
    of @{B}PowerUP @{UB}but forget, that there are almost none @{B}AMIGA@{UB}-OS compatible shared
    libraries for PowerUP available).

  * There  was  a  quite  severe  bug  in  the  scheduler,  which  could lead to
    multitasking hang-ups in some special situations. This is corrected now.

  * The   function   'FreeVecPPC'   sometimes   could  trash  several  registers
    (especially when freeing large amount of memory). This is corrected now.

@{I}Software/Tools@{UI}

  * In  the  @{B}WarpUP  4 @{UB} distribution  the  @{B}PowerUP @{UB} emulation  of @{I}Frank Wille @{UI}is
    provided.  The core of this emulation is a 'ppc.library', which, in contrary
    to  the original 'ppc.library' of @{B}Phase5@{UB}, works under @{B}WarpOS@{UB}. This way it is
    possible  to  run  @{B}PowerUP @{UB} applications under @{B}WarpOS@{UB}, in parallel to @{B}WarpUP@{UB}
    applications.

    The  current version of the @{B}PowerUP @{UB}emulation is @{B}V0.6 @{UB}and it requires @{B}WarpUP
    4 @{UB}('powerpc.library V15').

    It  is  strongly  recommended  to  read  the corresponding text files in the
    directory  'PowerUPEmu',  to  make the software working correctly and to get
    aware of all restrictions (mainly concerning compatibility).

    IMPORTANT:  the  @{B}WarpUP  V4 @{UB} installer  always  sets the terminator variable
    'powerpc/terminator'   to  2.  This  setting  leads  to  the  best  possible
    reliability of @{B}WarpOS @{UB}itself, but has the effect, that the @{B}PowerUP @{UB}emulation
    and  @{B}WarpOS @{UB} don't work together anymore. @{B}CyberStormPPC @{UB}users should set the
    variable to zero, if the @{B}PowerUP @{UB}emulation should be used. @{B}BlizzardPPC @{UB}users
    have a more difficult job (thanks to the Flash ROM) and should read the file
    'PowerUPEmu/README'.

  * In  the  directory 'tools/BPPCFix' there is a tool (again from @{I}Frank Wille@{UI}),
    which  allows  to  reboot  a  @{B}BlizzardPPC @{UB} based  system  in a way, that the
    'ppc.library'  is  not  started  anymore after reboot. This leads to a major
    improvement  of  the situation for the @{B}BlizzardPPC @{UB}users, because they don't
    have  to  use  the  dirty  termination  procedure  anymore  to launch @{B}WarpUP@{UB}
    applications.    For    more    information    please    read    the    file
    'tools/BPPCFix/BPPCFix.readme'.

  * In  the  directory  'tools' there is the program 'WarpStat', which shows the
    load  of the CPU and of the different task using a graphical user interface.
    This program requires @{B}MUI@{UB}.

If    you    have    any   question   on   @{B}WarpUP@{UB},   please   contact   us   at:
@{I}warpup-support@haage-partner.com@{UI}

You can download @{B}WarpUP 4 @{UB}from @{B}www.haage-partner.com/wu_sup_e.htm@{UB}
